module.exports = {"name":"Julien Vanharen","position":"Research engineer","position_date_start":"2020-06-01","birth_date":"1989-07-31","birth_place":"Soissons, France","citizenship":"French","mail":"julien.vanharen@onera.fr","phone":"+33 (0)6 60 74 88 16","website":"https://jvanhare.github.io/","github":"https://github.com/jvanhare","scholar":"https://scholar.google.com/citations?hl=en&user=R6OO3noAAAAJ","address":"22-24, avenue Marcellin Berthelot, Apt. A302, 92320 Châtillon France","company":{"name":"ONERA","team":"DMPE/PLM","name_alt":"The French Aerospace Lab","website":"https://www.onera.fr/en"},"research_interests":[{"keyword":"Computational Fluid Dynamics"},{"keyword":"Steady and unsteady Navier-Stokes simulations on industrial configurations"},{"keyword":"High-order and high-fidelity numerical methods"},{"keyword":"Anisotropic unstructured mesh adaptation"},{"keyword":"High-order mesh adaptation"},{"keyword":"Finite Volume and Finite Element Methods"},{"keyword":"Reynolds-Averaged Navier–Stokes (RANS) simulations"},{"keyword":"Large Eddy Simulation (LES)"},{"keyword":"High Performance Computing"}],"experience":[{"title":"Research engineer","show":true,"company":"ONERA - The French Aerospace Lab","company_url":"https://www.onera.fr/en","location":"Châtillon, France","date_start":"2020-06-01","description":"<a href=\"https://cedre.onera.fr/\" target=\"\\_blank\">CEDRE</a> developer","objectives":[{"obj":"Development of the <a href='https://cedre.onera.fr/' target=\"\\_blank\">CEDRE</a> suite"},{"obj":"High-order and high-fidelity numerical methods"},{"obj":"High Performance Computing optimization"}]},{"title":"Postdoctoral Fellow","show":true,"company":"Inria Saclay - Île-de-France","company_url":"https://www.inria.fr/en/centre-inria-saclay-ile-de-france","location":"Palaiseau, France","date_start":"2017-05-01","date_end":"2020-05-31","description":"Time-Accurate Anisotropic Mesh Adaptation for Fluid-Structure Interaction Simulations","objectives":[{"obj":"Implementation and validation of the Finite Element method for the unsteady linear elasticity equations"},{"obj":"Coupling with a code solving the Euler equations based on the Finite Volume method"},{"obj":"Development of error estimates for fluid-structure interaction applied to unsteady anisotropic mesh adaptation"},{"obj":"Project RAPID funded by Direction Générale de l'Armement (DGA)"}]},{"title":"Research engineer","show":false,"company":"CERFACS","company_url":"https://cerfacs.fr","location":"Toulouse, France","date_start":"2014-01-01","date_end":"2014-03-31","description":"Computational Fluid Dynamics & High-Order Numerical Methods","objectives":[{"obj":"URANS computations on unstructured meshes"},{"obj":"Stability of the Spectral Difference Method"}]},{"title":"Research intern","show":false,"company":"CERFACS","company_url":"https://cerfacs.fr","location":"Toulouse, France","date_start":"2013-04-01","date_end":"2013-09-30","description":"Numerical Methods for Nonconforming Grid Interface","objectives":[{"obj":"Theorerical and numerical analysis of nonconforming grid interface between structured blocks for Large Eddy Simulation,"},{"obj":"Implementation inside the <a href='http://elsa.onera.fr' target=\"\\_blank\">elsA</a> software of a Riemann solver at the interface."}]},{"title":"Engineering intern","show":false,"company":"AIRBUS","company_url":"https://www.airbus.com","location":"Bremen, Germany","date_start":"2012-06-01","date_end":"2012-08-31","description":"Handling Qualities","objectives":[{"obj":"A340-600 MSN360 flight test analysis"},{"obj":"Effect of the vortex generators on rudder efficiency"}]},{"title":"Engineering intern","show":false,"company":"AIRBUS","company_url":"https://www.airbus.com","location":"Toulouse, France","date_start":"2011-07-01","date_end":"2012-05-31","description":"Methods & Tools for Unsteady Numerical Simulations on Moving Meshes","objectives":[{"obj":"Unsteady aerodynamics, gust and aileron deflection effect on aircraft behaviour,"},{"obj":"Extension and improvement of CFD methods to predict flutter thanks to dynamic coupling,"},{"obj":"Selected to be part of the EADS Junior Programme."}]}],"education":[{"title":"Ph.D. Computational Fluid Dynamics","show":true,"pdf":"PhD_Vanharen_2017.pdf","company":"AIRBUS","company_url":"https://www.airbus.com","institution":"Université de Toulouse","institution_url":"https://www.univ-toulouse.fr/","location":"Toulouse, France","date_start":"2014-05-01","date_end":"2017-04-30","description":"High-Order Numerical Methods For Unsteady Flows Around Complex Geometries","objectives":[{"obj":"Collaboration between <a href='https://www.airbus.com' target=\"\\_blank\">AIRBUS</a> & <a href='https://cerfacs.fr' target=\"\\_blank\">CERFACS</a>"},{"obj":"Several numerical methods & codes are investigated for industrial applications"},{"obj":"The coupling with a nonconforming grid interface of high-order schemes for structured and unstructured zones in <a href='http://elsa.onera.fr' target=\"\\_blank\">elsA</a>"},{"obj":"The Spectral Difference Method in <a href='http://gpuigt.free.fr/jaguar.html' target=\"\\_blank\">JAGUAR</a>"},{"obj":"The Lattice Boltzmann Methods in <a href='http://www.prolb-cfd.com/' target=\"\\_blank\">ProLB</a>"}]},{"title":"Argonne Training Program on Extreme-Scale Computing (ATPESC)","show":true,"institution":"Argonne National Laboratory","institution_url":"https://extremecomputingtraining.anl.gov","location":"Lemont, IL, USA","date_start":"2016-07-31","date_end":"2016-08-12","description":"Intensive, two-week training on the key skills, approaches, and tools to design, implement, and execute computational science and engineering applications on current high-end computing systems and the leadership-class computing systems of the future","objectives":[{"obj":"Computer architectures and predicted evolution"},{"obj":"Numerical algorithms and mathematical software"},{"obj":"Approaches to building community codes for HPC systems"},{"obj":"Data analysis, visualization, I/O, and methodologies and tools for big data applications"},{"obj":"Performance measurement and debugging tools"}]},{"title":"M.Sc. Fluid Dynamics","show":true,"institution":"ISAE-SUPAERO","institution_url":"https://www.isae-supaero.fr/en/","location":"Toulouse, France","date_start":"2012-09-01","date_end":"2013-06-30"},{"title":"M.Sc. Aerospace & Aeronautical Engineering","show":true,"institution":"ISAE-SUPAERO","institution_url":"https://www.isae-supaero.fr/en/","location":"Toulouse, France","date_start":"2009-09-01","date_end":"2013-06-30"},{"title":"Classe Préparatoire PCSI/PC","show":false,"institution":"Lycée Faidherbe","institution_url":"https://www.faidherbe.org/","location":"Lille, France","date_start":"2007-09-01","date_end":"2009-06-30","description":"Undergraduate studies in a national preparatory program for entrance into France state run graduate school of engineering"}],"teaching":[{"title":"Incompressible fluid mechanics [MF102]","institution":"ENSTA Paris","institution_url":"https://www.ensta-paris.fr/","location":"Palaiseau, France","date":"2019-06-01","description":"The goal of this course is to lay out the fundamental concepts and results for the incompressible fluid mechanics.","objectives":[{"obj":"Characteristic quantities of an incompressible flow"},{"obj":"Dimensional analysis"},{"obj":"Navier-Stokes equations"},{"obj":"Boundary layer concepts"},{"obj":"Matched asymptotic expansions"},{"obj":"Falkner–Skan boundary layer"}]},{"title":"Fundamentals to understand and analyze high fidelity compressible Large Eddy Simulation (LES)","institution":"CERFACS","institution_url":"https://cerfacs.fr","location":"Toulouse, France","date":"2016-05-01","description":"This training course enables the participants to reinforce their theoretical knowledge in order to understand and analyze high fidelity compressible Large Eddy Simulation (LES) and hands-on sessions are organized to put the theoretical courses into practice","objectives":[{"obj":"Numerical simulation for the Navier-Stokes equations (mesh, discretization methods, data storage)"},{"obj":"High-fidelity numerical schemes for LES"},{"obj":"Signal processing and unsteady turbulence modeling"},{"obj":"Turbulence injection methods"},{"obj":"Navier-Stokes Characteristic Boundary Conditions (NSCBC)"},{"obj":"Wall treatment"}]}],"seminars":[{"title":"Anisotropic mesh adaptation. Theory and applications.","html":"https://jvanhare.github.io/slides/","pdf":"toto.pdf","institution":"CEA-Cesta","institution_url":"https://www.cea.fr/english","location":"Le Barp, France","date":"2021-01-22","link":"Jan_2021_CEA","abstract":"Computational Fluid Dynamics (CFD) entered the aerospace industry some decades ago. During the last 20 years, the focus was mainly on increasing solver robustness and accuracy. However, obvious as it may be, no mesh implies no solution and the latter depends on the mesh quality. Indeed, mesh and solution should be seen as a couple. The numerical schemes and the mesh generation methods have to be tightly linked. A very efficient approach to address these challenges is the anisotropic unstructured mesh adaptation and the vertex-centered Mixed Finite Element Finite Volume (MFEFV) method. First of all, an emphasis is put on the theory of anisotropic unstructured meshes and error estimates for steady and unsteady flow simulations. The cavity operator, including its non-manifold version, is then presented to obtain, strictly speaking, the anisotropic mesh. To conclude with the theoretical aspects, the key principles of the MFEFV method are presented. Finally, this whole framework is illustrated by two major applications: a fluid-structure interaction problem dealing with an elastic panel in shock tube and the C608 low boom flight demonstrator test case from the third AIAA Sonic Boom Prediction Workshop (SBPW)."}],"lang":[{"name":"French","level":"Native proficiency"},{"name":"English","level":"Full working proficiency"},{"name":"German","level":"Good working knowledge"},{"name":"Polish","level":"Basic communication skills"}]}